lenge under Article of the Constitution of India In Khoday Distilleries Ltd v State of Karnataka Judge Bench this Court held It is next submitted before us that the amended Rules are arbitrary unreasonable and cause undue hardship and therefore violate Article of the Constitution Although the protection of Article g may not be available to the appellants the Rules must undoubtedly satisfy the test of Article which is a guarantee against arbitrary action However one must bear in mind that what is being challenged here under Article is not executive action but delegated legislation The tests of arbitrary action which apply to executive actions do not necessarily apply to delegated legislation In order that delegated legislation can be struck down such legislation must be manifestly arbitrary a law which could not be reasonably expected to emanate from an authority delegated with the law making power In Indian Express Newspapers Bombay P Ltd v Union of India SCC SCC Tax this Court said that a piece of subordinate legislation does not carry the same degree of immunity which is enjoyed by a statute passed by a competent legislature A subordinate legislation may be questioned under Article on the ground that it is unreasonable unreasonable not in the sense of not being reasonable but in the sense that it is manifestly SCC SCC W P C of Ors arbitrary Drawing a comparison between the law in England and in India the Court further observed that in England the Judges would say Parliament never intended the authority to make such Rules they are unreasonable and ultra vires In India arbitrariness is not a separate ground since it will come within the embargo of Article of the Constitution But subordinate legislation must be so arbitrary that it could not be said to be in conformity with the statute or that it offends Article of the Constitution Emphasis supplied In Shayara Bano v Union of India Ors Judge Bench RF Nariman J while dissenting with the majority observed Manifest arbi